# Literature Review: Towards Defining Industry 5.0 Vision with Intelligent and Softwarized Wireless

Network Architectures and Services: A Survey

## Introduction

The rapid advancement in wireless network technologies has led to the emergence of Industry 5.0, which
aims to integrate intelligent and softwarized wireless network architectures and services into various
industries. This literature review explores the potential of Industry 5.0 and the role of advanced wireless
network technologies in its realization. The review synthesizes relevant research findings and highlights
knowledge gaps that require further investigation.

## Integration of 6G Wireless Networks with Advanced Architectures and Networks

The integration of 6G wireless networks with advanced architectures and networks, such as software-defined networks (SDN), network functions virtualization (NFV), and cloud/fog computing, is crucial for
the realization of Industry 5.0. Zeb et al. (2022) discuss the potential use cases of 6G networks in smart
healthcare and Industry 5.0. They emphasize the need for intelligent next-generation (NextG) wireless
networks as technological enablers for Industry 5.0. These networks can leverage advanced architectures
and networks to provide efficient and reliable wireless communication services.

## Challenges and Requirements of 6G Networks

The deployment of 6G networks poses several challenges and requires specific requirements to meet
the demands of Industry 5.0. Akbar et al. (2022) provide a comprehensive survey on the challenges,
requirements, applications, key enabling technologies, use cases, AI integration issues, and security
aspects of 6G networks. They highlight the need for efficient AI integration and security mechanisms
to ensure the reliable operation of 6G networks in Industry 5.0 environments.

## Potential Use of Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAVs) in Industry 5.0

Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) have shown great potential for various applications in Industry 5.0.
A study by [Anonymous] proposes a system called iSALSA, which utilizes UAVs for automated site
surveys in rugged environments to design industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) networking solutions. The
iSALSA system also enables pre-deployment simulation and validation of access points (APs), improving
